Appendix 1 - Real Capstone
The capstone I submitted was the assignment.
What followed changed me from student to leader.
After submitting the Capstone, I kept building. Not because I had to. Because I wanted to.
The original Unwind implementation was mechanical Python. It was deterministic. If I defined the rules correctly, the system behaved. That felt safe.
But I built this tool to work with people, not machines.
And that exposed a tension I didn’t see at first:
You can build something mechanically pure that no one wants to use because it has zero attunement.
Or you can build something deeply attuned that slowly drifts away from its original intent.
The intent of this tool is not to feed story. It’s to interrupt story and bring someone back to what is actually here.
Mechanical purity gives you structure.
Attunement gives you life.
Getting both at once is hard.
When I put an LLM inside it, everything shifted.
The model didn’t break. It optimized. It collapsed stages. It moved toward resolution faster than I wanted. It sounded more human — but it cut tension prematurely.
We gained attunement — but we were losing purity.
My instinct was to add more rules.
That didn’t work.
The more rules I added, the heavier and more brittle the system became. The model still optimized around them. That’s when I realized something important:
AI was not going to solve the design problem for me.
It would amplify whatever direction I pointed it in.
It didn’t give me the insight to turn rules into goals.
It didn’t suggest separating structure from improvisation.
It didn’t tell me the finish line was wrong.
Those insights came from sitting with the problem long enough.
Eventually it became clear:
You don’t control an LLM with more rules.
You design around its optimization behavior.
So instead of forcing compliance, I reframed the architecture.
Phases became structured method steps.
The backend enforces sequence integrity — no jumping from Phase 1 to Phase 3.
But inside each phase, the LLM has freedom.
Like a skilled salesperson: there are stages — you don’t go straight to the bedroom. But within each stage, you improvise. The user should never feel like the model is reading from a script.
Structure without rigidity.
Improvisation without drift.
The model can suggest advancement, but the system decides what prompt it is allowed to see. No skipped modules are even visible.
That separation — structure enforced by the system, improvisation handled by the model — changed everything.
The same pattern repeated with measurement.
At one point I asked: how do we know if a session worked? Letting the model declare success felt wrong. What if the user felt clearer but the model didn’t label it correctly?
AI didn’t give me the answer.
The answer was obvious once I stopped asking it.
Ask the user.
Measure charge at the beginning. Measure it at the end. Let the backend route based on change in charge. The model does not get to declare success.
Ownership became clear.
Economics forced another breakthrough.
The prompt grew to 25 pages. I ran the numbers. Cost per session. Required margin. Would a user pay that? Suddenly modularization wasn’t philosophical — it was financial.
We split the prompt into phase modules. Loaded only what was needed. Economics improved architecture.
AI didn’t suggest that.
Math did.
Then there was the Replit moment.
AI initially insisted I would need to build everything from scratch. Estimated 150 hours. High complexity. High risk.
I pushed back. I researched Replit. I demonstrated what it could scaffold. The estimate dropped dramatically.
That wasn’t AI insight.
That was leadership.
Later, when building the risky 20% value-add components, AI warned against using agents for complex logic. That’s when branching became real. Freeze the stable 80% infrastructure — auth, database, payments. Break the remaining work into chunks. Build them in branches. If an agent fails, revert. No risk to the core.
Branches stopped being theory from MSSE.
They became lived risk mitigation.
Over and over, I saw the same pattern:
AI does not feel misalignment.
AI does not sit in ambiguity.
AI does not sense when something is slightly off.
AI does not hold a vision.
It generates.
Working with AI is not just being a contractor. It’s being the architect and the business owner.
The trades build from drawings.
The contractor coordinates.
But someone has to hold the vision of what is being built — and why.
That part cannot be outsourced.
The real insights didn’t come from asking better prompts.
They came from sitting with the problem long enough that the right constraints emerged.
Not quickly. Not efficiently.
But because I stayed with it.
Through this process I gained something more important than a working app.
I gained confidence to lead.
To push back when something feels wrong.
To simplify instead of escalate.
To measure instead of speculate.
To let economics shape architecture.
To branch and experiment without fear.
To step into the unknown and trust I would find the structure.
The mechanical version tried to enforce depth.
The LLM version forced me to understand depth.
That difference matters.
This became my real capstone.
Not because of the grade.
Because I now understand that building with AI is not about control.
It is about constraint, judgment, economics, patience, and leadership.
And that only comes from staying with the problem yourself.
